occurrences.line_text: But her two other sisters standing by,
And those two froward sisters, their faire loues
And quite contrary to her sisters kind;
And with his goodly sisters, Graces three;
Till that her sisters children, woxen strong
There those fiue sisters had continuall trade,
Amongst her watry sisters by a pond,
Whiles all her sisters did for her lament,
And all her sisters, that with her did sit,
But yet his sisters skill vnto him lent
To the three fatall sisters house she went.
Not for thine owne, but for thy sisters sake,
No lesse then do her elder sisters broode.
And Sisyphus an huge round stone did reele
With goodly purposes there as they sit:
Thrise euery weeke in ashes she did sit,
The cloud of death did sit. Which doen away,
Did on so weake foundation euer sit:
Doest thou sit wayling by black Stygian lake,
Where many soules sit wailing woefully,
But still twixt feare and hope amazd does sit,
And chauft, that any on his backe should sit;
And he that high does sit, and all things see
On which they lowly sit, and fitting purpose frame.
On which the drery death did sit, as sad
Fast by her side did sit the bold Sans-loy
No braunch, whereon a fine bird did not sit:
There, as in glistring glory she did sit,
Did sit, as yet ashamd, how rude Pan did her dight.
For thy the first did in the forepart sit,
For neuer wight so fast in sell could sit,
And all her sisters, that with her did sit,
The whiles the Nymphes sit all about him round,
And bidding her sit downe, to rest her faint
To sit in second seat of soueraigne king,
To sit and rest the walkers wearie shankes,
To sit in his owne seate, his cause to end,
Dread Souerayne Goddesse, that doest highest sit
He maketh Kings to sit in souerainty;
By any skill or labour it would sit,
So brought vnto his Lord, where he did sit,
And bid him eate, henceforth he oft shall hungry sit.
Where she might sit nigh to the den alone,
Thus she did sit in souerayne Maiestie,
Thus did she sit in royall rich estate,
That he besought him downe by him to sit,
But without sword vpon his thigh to sit:
They prayd him sit, and gaue him for to feed
That most in Pastorellaes grace did sit.
But Nymphes and Faeries by the bancks did sit,
And in her soueraine Maiesty to sit,
But onely mongst the rest by her to sit,
And in his costly Bath causd to bee site:
It sited was in fruitfull soyle of old,
Not so (quoth she) but sith that heauens king
Sith cruell fates the carefull threeds vnfould,
But sith the heauens, and your faire handeling
Sith to thee is vnknowne the cradle of thy brood.
Sith none, that breatheth liuing aire, does know,
Sith Vna now he algates must forgoe,
Sith that false Traytour did my honour reaue?
Sith her Prince Arthur of proud ornaments
For sith I know your goodly gouernaunce,
Sith him in Faerie court he late auizd;
Sith heauen thee deignes to hold in liuing state,
But sith this wretched woman ouercome
Sith last I left that honorable place,
Sith his good steed is lately from him gone;
Sith earst into this forrest wild I came.
Vnlucky Squire (said Guyon) sith thou hast
But sith in might thou didst my mercy proue,
And sith for me ye fight, to me this grace
Well could he him remember, sith of late
Sith late with him I batteil vaine would boste;
But sith thou hast found fauour in mine eye,
Well knew they both his person, sith of late
What doe I recke, sith that he dyde entire?
Sith wrathfull hand wrought not her owne desire?
Yet sith his fate so cruelly did fall,
That sith I armes and knighthood first did plight,
Sith of that Goddesse I haue sought the sight,
Sith now he is farre from his monstrous swarme,
Sith it is shrined in my Soueraines brest,
Thus farre forth pardon, sith that choicest wit
For neuer yet, sith warlike armes he bore,
Yet sith they warlike armes haue layd away:
And sith it is vneath to find his haunt,
Sith him whilome in Britaine she did vew,
Sith a sore euill, which this virgin bright
And sayd, Sith then thou knowest all our griefe,
Or what needs her to toyle, sith fates can make
Sith which it had bin here preseru'd in store,
How can they other do, sith both are bold and blind?
Sith other offices for mother meet
Farewell my sweetest sonne, sith we no more shall meet.
Sith her whylome vpon high Pindus hill,
Sith I her dew reward cannot restore:
Sith that in saluage forests she did dwell,
Sith brought she was now to so hard constraint,
And loue to frenzy turnd, sith loue is franticke hight.
Sith him he saw still stronger grow through strife,
Sith dint of steele his carcas could not quell:
The hart out of his brest: for sith her ded
Sith then (said Braggadocchio) needes thou wilt
Sith late mischaunce had her compeld to chaunge
But thou good man, sith farre in sea we bee,
But sith that none of all her knights is nye,
Then tooke he him yet trembling sith of late,
But sith the Sunne now ginnes to slake his beames,
Sith all thy worthy prayses being blent,
What to Aeneas fell; sith that men sayne
Yet sith he n'ote saue both, he sau'd that same,
Sith late he fled from his too earnest foe:
Sith I enioyd the gentlest Dame aliue;
And humbly thanked him a thousand sith,
For sith the houre, that first he did them let
Sith that more bounteous creature neuer far'd
Sith powre of hand, nor skill of learned brest,
Should be remedilesse, sith none but hee,
So none should be out shut, sith all of loues were fitted.
Sith she her selfe was of his grace indigne:
Hope to endure, sith workes of heauenly wits
Sith each of them his Ladie had him by,
And said, Sir Knight, sith ye this Lady clame,
But reade you Sir, sith ye my name haue hight,
That rather seemes, sith knowen armes ye shonne.
Let me this craue, sith first I was defyde,
Feared in vaine, sith meanes ye see there wants theretoo.
My Amoret, sith you her freed fro thence,
Sith to his powre we all are subiect borne:
Sith now of dayes such temperance is rare
Sith loue was first the ground of all her griefe,
Mote we entreat you, sith this gentle crew
Which sith they cannot in this Canto well
Might be my lucky lot; sith all by lot we hold.
Sith no lesse famous then the rest they bee,
Sith then (sayd he) ye both the dead deny,
Sith neither force of stones which they did throw,
Sith thou misdeem'st so much of things in sight?
Sith of things subiect to thy daily vew
Then sith ye needs (quoth he) will know my shame,
Her to obay, sith he his faith had plight,
I trust a liue, sith I thee fostred first;
In stupid sorow, sith thy iuster merit
Sith shady dampe had dimd the heauens reach,
Certes (sayd she) sith ye so well haue spide
But sith ye please, that both our blames shall die,
Sith in th'Almighties euerlasting seat
Yet sith he heard but one, that did appeare,
Sith ye thus farre haue tendred my poore case,
Sith which she hath me euer since abhord,
Sith no redemption nigh she did nor heare nor see.
But sith that he is gone irreuocable,
Nathelesse, sith ye so courteous seemed late,
Therefore, good Sir, sith now occasion fit
Sith his own thought he knew most cleare from wite.
Sith then ye needs will know the griefe I hoord,
Sith he cannot expresse his simple minde,
But sith we need good counsell (sayd the swaine)
But onely breath sith that I did forgiue.
Sith he likewise did wrong by him sustaine,
Now Lady sith your fortunes thus dispose,
And toyle endured, sith I left him last
Sith they know best, what is the best for them:
Sith each vnto himselfe his life may fortunize.
Sith in his powre she was to foe or frend;
Sith they that were the cause of all, were gone.
Sith otherwise he could not mend thing past;
Tho Coridon he prayd, sith he well knew
And loued for his prowesse, sith they twaine
Was that same infant, which so long sith past
Sithence I loathed haue my life to lead,
He lately tooke, and sithence kept as thrall.
Great threasure sithence we did finde contained;
But faire Fidessa, sithens fortunes guile,
Yet sithens silence lesseneth not my fire,
Yet sithens helpe, he saw, he needed more
Sithens it hath infixed faster hold
With holy father sits not with such things to mell.
How ill it sits with that same siluer hed
Then loe, where bound she sits, who[m]; thou hast sought,
He said; ï¿½ soueraigne Lord that sit'st on hye,
Full iolly knight he seemd, and faire did sitt,
But yet I warne thee now assured sitt,
Such one vile Enuie was, that fift in row did sitt.
Ne sittest downe on that same siluer stoole,
And sitting high; for lowly she did hate:
That cursed man, low sitting on the ground,
Of turtle doues, she sitting in an yuorie chaire.
One sitting idle on a sunny bancke,
Whereas he sitting found in secret shade
Sitting alone, his bitter lips did bight,
Whiles sad Celeno, sitting on a clift,
Of British bloud, all sitting at his bord;
Vpon the banck they sitting did espy
A seemely Maiden, sitting by the shore,
Whom they found sitting on a sumptuous bed,
And sitting downe vpon the rocky shore,
Sitting beside a fountaine in a rew,
Where sitting on the flore the Hag she found,
Sitting beside his mother on the ground;
There she them found, all sitting round about
Sitting in shade beside his grazing steede;
Shee sitting by him as on ground he lay,
Sitting in couert shade of arbors sweet,
But one old woman sitting there beside,
A gentle Faulcon sitting on an hill,
Now walking soft, now sitting still vpright,
So sitting high in dreaded souerayntie,
Who sitting with his Lady then at bord,
Whereas his loue was sitting all alone,
Sitting beside his Ladie there at ease,
And sitting carelesse on the scorners stoole,
And sitting downe, her selfe a while bethought
Whom by the Altar he doth sitting find,
Sitting like King of fowles in maiesty and powre.
Tho sitting downe by them vpon the greene,
Whereas the Bowre of Blisse was situate;
And strong aduizement of six wisards old,
But this was drawne of six vnequall beasts,
On which her six sage Counsellours did ryde,
And her to serue six yeares in warlike wize,
Soone as the terme of those six yeares shall cease,
That now there do but two of six remaine;
And eke those six, which lately with her fought,
And those six Knights that Ladies Champions,
He the six Islands, comprouinciall
On which she saw sixe knights, that did darraine
That none of all the sixe before, him durst assay.
Bad those same sixe forbeare that single enimy.
These sixe would me enforce by oddes of might,
Certes (said she) then bene ye sixe to blame,
Then spake one of those sixe, There dwelleth here
And all sixe brethren, borne of one parent,
But one of those sixe knights, Gardante hight,
Thus marched these sixe couples forth in faire degree.
And at th'one side sixe iudges were dispos'd,
In which his worke he had sixe seruants prest,
All sixe strong groomes, but one then other more:
Sixe they were all, all full of fell despight,
Bearing his sixe deformed heads on hye,
Then came those sixe sad brethren, like forlorne,
Sixe valiant Knights, of one faire Nymphe yborne,
And with him sixe knights more, which enterpriz'd
All sixe well seene in armes, and prou'd in many a fight.
Sixe of thy fellowes of the best array,
The sixt had charge of them now being dead,
From the fourth houre of night vntill the sixt;
And is the Virgin, sixt in her degree,
The sixt was Lansack, a redoubted Knight:
Twise sixteen warders sat, all armed bright
High Swale, vnquiet Nide, and troublous Skell;
At last faire Hesperus in highest skie
Cleare as the skie, withouten blame or blot,
To whom he thus: ï¿½ fairest vnder skie,
Weening it had beene thunder in the skie,
More swift, then swallow sheres the liquid skie,
Two Paynim knights, all armd as bright as skie,
For th'aire was milde, and cleared was the skie,
Like as the shining skie in summers night,
But that it all the skie doth ouercast
As thicke as hayle forth poured from the skie:
As Ioue will haue aduaunced to the skie,
A watry cloud doth ouercast the skie,
Like as the lightning brond from riuen skie,
That seem'd his shrikes would rend the brasen skie:
She were as faire as any vnder skie.
Like to a storme, which houers vnder skie
The ioy of Gods and men, that vnder skie
Long Rhodanus, whose sourse springs from the skie;
These towring rocks, which reach vnto the skie,
In fearefull darkenesse, furthest from the skie,
Like Eyas hauke vp mounts vnto the skies,
That as a cloud doth seeme to dim the skies;
And lift it selfe vnto the highest skies?
He vp gan lift toward the azure skies,
Vp to the skies, whence first deriu'd it was,
As if they would haue rent the brasen skies.
Then Elfinor, who was in Magick skild;
And throughly skild in vse of shield and speare;
A Painim knight, that well in armes was skild,
Let them record them, that are better skild,
And so well skild; nathlesse he takes great ioy
For that to her he seem'd best skild in righteous lore.
For both were skild in that experiment,
The fift Armeddan, skild in louely layes;
And better skild in Tilt and Turnament,
But Calidore, that was well skild in fight,
Who all in rage to see his skilfull might
Where many skilfull leaches him abide,
And wondrous strong by nature, and by skilfull frame.
Their natiue musicke by her skilfull art:
The skilfull Palmer formally did frame.
For Artegall in swimming skilfull was,
As when a skilfull Marriner doth reed
Ne skilfull of the vncouth ieopardy;
The earth shall sooner leaue her kindly skill
In deepest Hell, and framd by Furies skill,
Ne let the man ascribe it to his skill,
Who by her wicked arts, and wylie skill,
Too false and strong for earthly skill or might,
Her curious skill, the warbling notes to play,
And so transformed from his former skill,
Which who hath skill them rightly to haue chusd,
For feare through want of skill her beautie to disgrace?
But chiefly skill to ride, seemes a science
Ne thenceforth his approued skill, to ward,
That no'te auoyded be by earthly skill or powre.
But him in strength and skill the Prince surpast,
Which goodly order, and great workmans skill
For skill in Musicke of all in her dayes,
Ne like in grace, ne like in learned skill;
And their sweet skill in wonted melody;
How then shall I, Apprentice of the skill,
Nought so of loue this looser Dame did skill,
Whence he indued was with skill so maruellous.
Then of my skill: who helpe may haue elsewhere,
And to him said, If any leaches skill,
The saluage minds with skill of iust and trew;
Ne ought ye want, but skill, which practize small
Who through foresight of his eternall skill,
(This Liagore whylome had learned skill
By her hid from the world, and from the skill
And euery where, where with my power or skill
That has no skill of Court nor courtesie,
Of gracious speach, and skill his words to frame
Sith powre of hand, nor skill of learned brest,
O wondrous skill, and sweet wit of the man,
By any ridling skill, or commune wit.
But yet his sisters skill vnto him lent
Their mother was a Fay, and had the skill
By wondrous skill, and many hidden wayes,
Ne lesse his skill in weapons did appeare,
As guilefull Goldsmith that by secret skill,
Or whether it through skill, or errour were.
Cast into sundry shapes by wondrous skill,
Farre passing that, which by surpassing skill
In all the skill of deeming wrong and right,
So feeble skill of perfect things the vulgar has.
By any skill or labour it would sit,
Who so vpon him selfe will take the skill
And then my loue (though now it little skill,)
The skill whereof to Princes hearts he doth reueale.
She wondred at the workemans passing skill,
But through great fury both their skill forgot,
That seekes to saue the subiect of her skill,
Thereto he had great skill in single fight:
Great skill it is such duties timely to bestow.
Which others, that haue greater skill in mind,
Ne all the skill, which that immortall spright
Through tempering of her words & lookes by wondrous skill.
By any skill out of his cruell hands;
For all that euer was by natures skill
To firends, to foes, which skill men call Ciuility.
Which to recure, no skill of Leaches art
Both his estate, and loue from skill of any wight.
Out quenched, leaues no skill nor difference of wight.
Of his young charge, whereof he skilled nought:
To skim those coastes, for bondmen there to buy,
And next her wrinkled skin rough sackcloth wore,
Her wrizled skin as rough, as maple rind,
Close creeping twixt the marrow and the skin.
And pierced to the skin, but bit no more,
And skin all withered like a dryed rooke,
That hid no whit her alablaster skin,
Which staines his snowy skin with hatefull hew:
But lightly rased her soft silken skin,
That deckt the azure field with her faire pouldred skin.
To looke on her faire face, and marke her snowy skin.
Made of Beares skin, that him more dreadfull made,
That dyde in sanguine red her skin all snowy cleene.
Casts off his ragged skin and freshly doth him dight.
His Lyons skin chaungd to a pall of gold,
For his loues sake his Lions skin vndight:
By whom a litle skippet floting did appeare.
They saw together skirmishing, as seemed:
Like twinckling starres, and all the skirt about
In a long purple pall, whose skirt with gold,
Whose skirts were bordred with bright sunny beams,
And at the Porter, skorning them so few,
Him selfe to saue: but he there slew him at the skreene.
Made of a dead mans skull, that seem'd a ghastly sight.
Seemd in their song to scorne the cruell sky.
And thou, O fairest Princesse vnder sky,
The great earthes wombe they open to the sky,
Defast the beautie of the shining sky,
But neither God of loue, nor God of sky
Emongst th'eternall spheres and lamping sky,
For he by words could call out of the sky
And vauted all within, like to the sky,
Reeking aloft, vprolled to the sky:
Ne chaunged was into a starre in sky:
And also those which wonne in th'azure sky?
Serues her, as any Princesse vnder sky,
No more then lightening from the lofty sky.
Sunne of the world, great glory of the sky,
So there all day they bode, till light the sky forsooke.
That purest skye with brightnesse they dismaid:
Her coleblacke curtein ouer brightest skye,
Then gan her beautie shine, as brightest skye,
That with his talnesse seemd to threat the skye,
O great Orgoglio, greatest vnder skye,
In his light wings, is lifted vp to skye:
Great Mammon, greatest god below the skye,
Of euery sort and nation vnder skye,
The fairest wight that wonneth vnder skye,
Most cursed of all creatures vnder skye,
When so the froward skye began to lowre:
Before that angry Gods, and cruell skye
Beholding it from far, do thinke it threates the skye.
As when two sunnes appeare in the azure skye,
That seemed to outshine the dimmed skye,
And rapt with whirling wheeles, inflames the skyen,
And with loud plaints importuneth the skyes,
The hell-bred beast threw forth vnto the skyes,
Did rend the ratling skyes with flames of fouldring heat.
At last when they had markt the chaunged skyes,
The flitting skyes, like flying Pursuiuant,
Mote deeme him borne with ill disposed skyes,
Vp to the skyes, that them of drowning made affeard.
Her mantle, colour'd like the starry skyes,
To scale the skyes, and put Ioue from his right:
In siluer sockets, shyning like the skyes,
Confounds both land & seas, and skyes doth ouercast.
They are the daughters of sky-ruling Ioue,
My cities sackt, and their sky-threating towres
Which stunck so vildly, that it forst him slacke
And thicke entangled knots adown does slacke.
Yet yield he would not, nor his rancour slacke.
Now when they spide the knight to slacke his pace,
And woxe halfe wroth against her damzels slacke,
Nor wearinesse to slacke her hast, but fled
And slacke attendaunce vnto straungers call.
Nor slacke her threatfull hand for daungers dout,
And cruell sword out of his fingers slacke
Yet neither would their fiendlike fury slacke,
For any thing wold slacke, but still vppon him hong.
Him slaies, drownes Lady Munera
And either both them drownes, or trayterously slaies.
She fights with Radigund, her slaies,
And slaieth him in field.
That good knight of the Redcrosse to haue slain:
His foes haue slaine themselues, with whom he should contend.
He thought haue slaine her in his fierce despight:
And would haue slaine them in his furious ire,
And cruelly was slaine, that shall I euer mone.
O leaue her soone, or let her soone be slaine.
Came forth, and finding Kirkrapine there slaine,
Haue slaine him straight: but when he sees his age,
Who when the shamed shield of slaine Sans foy
Him to haue slaine; when loe a darkesome clowd
What more? the Redcrosse knight was slaine with Paynim knife.
Him thought at first encounter to haue slaine,
For to haue slaine the man, that on the ground did lye.
Which there were slaine, as sheepe out of the fold,
Findes Mordant and Amauia slaine
Had slaine Sir Mordant, and his Lady bright:
The crowned often slaine, the slayer cround,
And many good knights slaine, that haue vs sought to saue.
At bold Canutus; but of him was slaine anon.
Disguised slaine, ere any thereof thought:
Yet in the chace was slaine of them, that fled:
But shortly was by Coyll in battell slaine:
Who flying from his guilt, by them was slaine,
Full litle wanted, but he had him slaine,
Till both the sonnes of Edwin he haue slaine,
Both slaine in battell vpon Layburne plaine,
From rash reuenge, she had him surely slaine,
Proud Sisera, and how Camill' hath slaine
Fiue dayes there be, since he (they say) was slaine,
And drunke with bloud of men, slaine by his might,
And in his rage his mother would haue slaine,
And finding not th'Hyena to be slaine,
The riuall slaine, the victour through the flood
Whom hauing slaine, through luckles arrowes glau[n]ce
He fell halfe dead; next stroke him should haue slaine,
Nations captiued, and huge armies slaine:
He for reuenge had guiltlesse Glauce slaine:
Seauen women by him slaine, and eaten clene.
And is by Arthure slaine.
And vow by Mahoune that he should be slaine.
And howld aloud to see his Lord there slaine,
This mightie man (quoth he) whom you haue slaine,
Was slaine: but that which is th'immortall spright
And offred streight the Lady to be slaine.
About that wofull couple, which were slaine,
To haue him slaine, or dearely doen aby.
The eldest of the which was slaine erewhile
And therefore ment him surely to haue slaine.
Of Guizor, by thee slaine, and murdred by thy slight.
Euen the bloud of Gyants, which were slaine,
Which late her folke had slaine, she bad the[m] forth to hold.
Her land, and slaine her children ruefully alas.
Them to haue stricken, and thrise to haue slaine.
And sure he had her slaine, had she not turnd her way.
His scattred people, ere they all were slaine,
Murdred my men, and slaine my Seneschall;
Hauing late slaine her Seneschall in fight,
In blood of knight, the which by thee is slaine,
I chaunst to meete this knight, who there lyes slaine,
